00:27:05.066 --> 00:27:07.836 A:middle
because you don't want
every little tick mark

00:27:07.836 --> 00:27:08.936 A:middle
to cause this click.

00:27:08.936 --> 00:27:10.266 A:middle
It would be too much.

00:27:11.656 --> 00:27:15.106 A:middle
Even playing at the major
tick marks could be too much.

00:27:16.046 --> 00:27:17.476 A:middle
The thing is, about haptics,

00:27:17.476 --> 00:27:19.276 A:middle
they can't overlap
with each other.

00:27:19.766 --> 00:27:22.106 A:middle
So let me play an illustration
of what we just saw.

00:27:23.516 --> 00:27:26.896 A:middle
[Clicking]

00:27:27.396 --> 00:27:30.496 A:middle
You can see here there's plenty
of space in between these clicks

00:27:30.816 --> 00:27:32.536 A:middle
for them to individually play

00:27:32.536 --> 00:27:34.456 A:middle
without them stomping
on each other.

00:27:35.336 --> 00:27:38.036 A:middle
But if we were adjusting this
volume with the Digital Crown,

00:27:38.036 --> 00:27:39.986 A:middle
that's fine if we're
rotating slowlily.

00:27:40.536 --> 00:27:42.396 A:middle
What if we did a quick
twist and it went

00:27:42.396 --> 00:27:43.866 A:middle
through those values
very quickly.

00:27:45.206 --> 00:27:46.826 A:middle
It would look more like this.

00:27:47.546 --> 00:27:49.906 A:middle
Now, the thing is,
this can't happen.

00:27:50.486 --> 00:27:52.906 A:middle
The Taptic Engine will
prevent these haptics

00:27:52.906 --> 00:27:54.616 A:middle
from playing simultaneously.

00:27:55.756 --> 00:28:01.246 A:middle
Instead it will play
the ones that it can.



00:27:55.756 --> 00:28:01.246 A:middle
Instead it will play
the ones that it can.

00:28:01.456 --> 00:28:04.166 A:middle
Now, this would result
in people hearing

00:28:04.166 --> 00:28:06.586 A:middle
and feeling less feedback
when they go quickly

00:28:06.586 --> 00:28:08.086 A:middle
than if they had gone slowly.

00:28:10.556 --> 00:28:12.196 A:middle
[Clicking noise]: We
only heard two cliques

00:28:12.766 --> 00:28:14.106 A:middle
when before we heard five.

00:28:14.576 --> 00:28:15.796 A:middle
That would lead to confusion

00:28:15.796 --> 00:28:19.106 A:middle
about how much the
value had been adjusted.

00:28:19.106 --> 00:28:21.586 A:middle
With this haptic,
use it judiciously.

00:28:22.276 --> 00:28:23.886 A:middle
Exercise restraint.

00:28:24.776 --> 00:28:29.176 A:middle
Just remember that haptics
can't play simultaneously.

00:28:29.176 --> 00:28:31.886 A:middle
For all haptics this
is good advice.

00:28:32.906 --> 00:28:35.976 A:middle
You should use them sparingly
to draw people's attention

00:28:36.246 --> 00:28:38.616 A:middle
to truly important
events in your app.

00:28:38.936 --> 00:28:41.386 A:middle
Their effectiveness
will diminish greatly

00:28:41.386 --> 00:28:45.266 A:middle
if everything a person does in
their app causes their watch

00:28:45.526 --> 00:28:47.056 A:middle
to vibrate and make sounds.

00:28:48.256 --> 00:28:52.346 A:middle
And please use these
haptic tones and patterns

00:28:52.346 --> 00:28:54.586 A:middle
as they were intended
to be used.

00:28:55.296 --> 00:28:58.276 A:middle
If haptic and auditory
feedback isn't used consistently

00:28:58.276 --> 00:29:01.226 A:middle
across all of the apps that
we make, they are going



00:28:58.276 --> 00:29:01.226 A:middle
across all of the apps that
we make, they are going

00:29:01.226 --> 00:29:02.156 A:middle
to lose their meaning.

00:29:02.506 --> 00:29:03.676 A:middle
We are all in this together.

00:29:04.056 --> 00:29:06.206 A:middle
We need to use these as they
are supposed to be used.

00:29:07.346 --> 00:29:11.076 A:middle
Okay. So quick recap
about Holistic Design.

00:29:11.466 --> 00:29:14.156 A:middle
Holistic Design is about
blurring the physical boundaries

00:29:14.156 --> 00:29:17.896 A:middle
between software and
hardware, getting your UI

00:29:17.896 --> 00:29:22.066 A:middle
to match the bezel color and
utilizing the Digital Crown

00:29:22.066 --> 00:29:24.896 A:middle
and the Force Touch display
and the Taptic Engine

00:29:25.176 --> 00:29:28.506 A:middle
to create a seamless connection
between software and hardware.

00:29:29.436 --> 00:29:33.526 A:middle
Okay. So let's move on to
the last major design theme

00:29:33.526 --> 00:29:36.776 A:middle
for Apple Watch and that
is lightweight interaction.

00:29:37.666 --> 00:29:39.836 A:middle
Lightweight interaction
means taking advantage

00:29:39.836 --> 00:29:42.796 A:middle
of the Watch's unique
position on the user's wrist

00:29:43.366 --> 00:29:45.806 A:middle
by offering them quick
and convenient access

00:29:45.856 --> 00:29:47.386 A:middle
to information and actions.

00:29:48.326 --> 00:29:51.256 A:middle
Interaction times in Apple
Watch are far more brief

00:29:51.666 --> 00:29:53.996 A:middle
than on an iPad or iPhone.

00:29:54.616 --> 00:29:58.526 A:middle
Interaction times on those
devices could be in the minutes

00:29:58.526 --> 00:30:01.336 A:middle
or even hours, whereas
interaction times



00:29:58.526 --> 00:30:01.336 A:middle
or even hours, whereas
interaction times

00:30:01.336 --> 00:30:03.416 A:middle
in Apple Watch are just
a matter of seconds.

00:30:04.426 --> 00:30:07.816 A:middle
Our internal metric for
interaction times is

00:30:07.816 --> 00:30:10.316 A:middle
about five seconds or less.

00:30:11.076 --> 00:30:13.726 A:middle
Checking your schedule,
going for a run,

00:30:14.076 --> 00:30:17.036 A:middle
replying to a text shouldn't
take longer than this.

00:30:18.206 --> 00:30:22.106 A:middle
You need to seriously consider
this when designing your app.

00:30:22.976 --> 00:30:25.656 A:middle
Designing for such
short interaction times

00:30:25.726 --> 00:30:26.996 A:middle
requires focus.

00:30:27.256 --> 00:30:31.036 A:middle
It requires focusing on the
most essential information

00:30:31.036 --> 00:30:33.716 A:middle
and actions and presenting
them as clearly

00:30:33.806 --> 00:30:35.376 A:middle
and legibly as possible.

00:30:36.256 --> 00:30:39.356 A:middle
You may need to drop
features if it takes too long

00:30:39.356 --> 00:30:41.326 A:middle
for people to accomplish tasks.

00:30:42.096 --> 00:30:43.926 A:middle
With that in mind, let's
look at how the concept

00:30:43.926 --> 00:30:47.636 A:middle
of lightweight can influence
how you design Glances,

00:30:47.676 --> 00:30:49.176 A:middle
Notifications and apps.

00:30:50.176 --> 00:30:51.266 A:middle
Let's start with Glances.

00:30:51.886 --> 00:30:54.606 A:middle
The name says it all,
it speaks volumes.

00:30:55.246 --> 00:30:58.396 A:middle
Glances are scannable
summaries of the information

00:30:58.396 --> 00:31:00.426 A:middle
that people seek
out most frequently



00:30:58.396 --> 00:31:00.426 A:middle
that people seek
out most frequently

00:31:00.806 --> 00:31:02.106 A:middle
from their favorite apps.

00:31:02.856 --> 00:31:06.226 A:middle
Your Glance may only be seen
on screen for a brief moment

00:31:06.226 --> 00:31:08.956 A:middle
in time as people swipe
from one Glance to another.

00:31:09.596 --> 00:31:12.896 A:middle
So focus on showing only the
most essential information

00:31:12.896 --> 00:31:16.306 A:middle
from your app and display
it as clearly as possible.

00:31:17.126 --> 00:31:19.796 A:middle
The purpose of the Weather
Glance is very clear.

00:31:20.306 --> 00:31:22.516 A:middle
Show people the current
weather conditions

00:31:22.516 --> 00:31:23.716 A:middle
in their current location.

00:31:24.456 --> 00:31:27.666 A:middle
This information is timely and
it's contextually relevant,

00:31:27.666 --> 00:31:30.256 A:middle
and it is the information
that people seek

00:31:30.256 --> 00:31:32.566 A:middle
out most frequently
from the Weather app.

00:31:33.706 --> 00:31:36.176 A:middle
Usually it's the only thing
that they want to know.

00:31:36.936 --> 00:31:39.566 A:middle
If they want to know
more like the forecast,

00:31:39.936 --> 00:31:41.656 A:middle
tapping the glance
will deep link

00:31:41.736 --> 00:31:44.236 A:middle
to an appropriate detail
screen within the app.

00:31:45.386 --> 00:31:48.046 A:middle
So even though the Glance
only shows a little bit

00:31:48.046 --> 00:31:51.986 A:middle
of information, more information
is just one tap away.

00:31:53.076 --> 00:31:56.096 A:middle
Try to strike a similar
balance with your Glance.

00:31:56.896 --> 00:31:58.726 A:middle
Display the most
frequently sought

00:31:58.726 --> 00:32:01.006 A:middle
after information from your app.



00:31:58.726 --> 00:32:01.006 A:middle
after information from your app.

00:32:01.876 --> 00:32:05.506 A:middle
Show information that is timely
and contextually relevant.

00:32:06.536 --> 00:32:09.276 A:middle
And make it easy for people
to get more information

00:32:09.376 --> 00:32:10.316 A:middle
by deep linking

00:32:10.316 --> 00:32:13.536 A:middle
to an appropriate
screen within your app.

00:32:13.536 --> 00:32:16.666 A:middle
And in addition, it is important
to communicate as clearly

00:32:16.666 --> 00:32:18.116 A:middle
and as efficiently as possible.

00:32:18.116 --> 00:32:20.956 A:middle
Even if you are only
showing just a few key pieces

00:32:20.956 --> 00:32:23.786 A:middle
of information, some of that
data might be more important

00:32:23.786 --> 00:32:24.496 A:middle
than the rest.

00:32:24.716 --> 00:32:27.596 A:middle
In the Weather Glance,
we immediately focus

00:32:27.596 --> 00:32:30.616 A:middle
on the current temperature
because it's so much larger

00:32:30.616 --> 00:32:32.766 A:middle
and brighter than the
rest of the information.

00:32:33.396 --> 00:32:35.906 A:middle
When there's just a few
elements on the screen,

00:32:36.076 --> 00:32:38.366 A:middle
there's more space for you
to do something like that

00:32:38.706 --> 00:32:42.636 A:middle
to draw people's attention to
one really key piece of data.

00:32:43.756 --> 00:32:46.376 A:middle
Graphics are also
a really good way

00:32:46.376 --> 00:32:48.466 A:middle
to communicate clearly
and efficiently.

00:32:48.986 --> 00:32:50.806 A:middle
The icon here makes it clear

00:32:50.806 --> 00:32:52.956 A:middle
that it is partly
cloudy outside.

00:32:53.736 --> 00:32:57.056 A:middle
Animations and graphs
are also great

00:32:57.096 --> 00:32:59.686 A:middle
for communicating
efficiently in your Glance.



00:33:00.686 --> 00:33:02.706 A:middle
It is also usually a good idea

00:33:02.706 --> 00:33:04.986 A:middle
to left align content
in your Glance.

00:33:05.826 --> 00:33:08.686 A:middle
Left aligned text for
most languages, at least,

00:33:09.206 --> 00:33:12.046 A:middle
tends to be more scannable
and it looks more orderly,

00:33:12.576 --> 00:33:15.386 A:middle
and it will help your
Glance to feel right at home

00:33:15.386 --> 00:33:17.116 A:middle
in the overall Glance UI.

00:33:18.676 --> 00:33:21.516 A:middle
Now when you start to design
your Glances, it is important

00:33:21.516 --> 00:33:23.736 A:middle
to know that Glances are
constructed from templates.

00:33:25.086 --> 00:33:28.016 A:middle
Glances are made by
combining one upper template

00:33:28.086 --> 00:33:30.316 A:middle
and one lower template.

00:33:31.756 --> 00:33:33.156 A:middle
This is a modular system.

00:33:33.586 --> 00:33:37.176 A:middle
There are 12 upper templates
and 24 lower templates

00:33:37.176 --> 00:33:38.236 A:middle
for you to choose from.

00:33:39.246 --> 00:33:41.506 A:middle
To make your Glance, you
just pick one of each.

00:33:42.306 --> 00:33:45.306 A:middle
Now, Glance templates
partially determine the size

00:33:45.366 --> 00:33:48.156 A:middle
and appearance of text,
which helps to ensure

00:33:48.156 --> 00:33:49.626 A:middle
that they are highly legible.

00:33:50.436 --> 00:33:53.826 A:middle
And Glance are also designed to
follow a consistent layout grid.

00:33:54.426 --> 00:33:55.976 A:middle
This helps to provide an element

00:33:55.976 --> 00:33:58.046 A:middle
of consistency across
all Glances.

00:33:58.596 --> 00:34:02.046 A:middle
Without this structure, the
overall Glance UI would start



00:33:58.596 --> 00:34:02.046 A:middle
Without this structure, the
overall Glance UI would start

00:34:02.046 --> 00:34:05.156 A:middle
to feel really cobbled together,
and that wouldn't be very great.

00:34:06.406 --> 00:34:08.326 A:middle
Enough about Glances.

00:34:08.766 --> 00:34:10.275 A:middle
Let's move on to notifications.

00:34:10.846 --> 00:34:14.946 A:middle
Notifications are a key aspect
of many Apple Watch experiences.

00:34:15.726 --> 00:34:18.456 A:middle
Notifications are all about
lightweight interaction.

00:34:19.516 --> 00:34:21.476 A:middle
The purpose of a notification is

00:34:21.505 --> 00:34:24.666 A:middle
to communicate high value
information clearly,

00:34:24.786 --> 00:34:26.126 A:middle
quickly and succinctly.

00:34:26.806 --> 00:34:30.516 A:middle
In order to accomplish this,
you want to use as few words

00:34:30.516 --> 00:34:34.766 A:middle
as possible and avoid
any unnecessary details.

00:34:35.636 --> 00:34:38.246 A:middle
Now even though the height
of a notification can scale

00:34:38.246 --> 00:34:41.065 A:middle
to accommodate its contents,
people don't want to read a lot

00:34:41.065 --> 00:34:42.806 A:middle
of text on their Apple Watch.

00:34:43.545 --> 00:34:44.806 A:middle
Get to the point quickly.

00:34:45.786 --> 00:34:48.936 A:middle
The notification that Calendar
sends when a meeting has started

00:34:48.936 --> 00:34:50.886 A:middle
and maybe you're running
a little bit late,

00:34:51.516 --> 00:34:52.926 A:middle
that's a good example of this.

00:34:53.246 --> 00:34:56.536 A:middle
There is no unnecessary
information or fluffy language.

00:34:56.976 --> 00:34:59.456 A:middle
Thirty-three minutes
ago, which meeting?



00:35:00.756 --> 00:35:03.236 A:middle
Today. 4:30 to 5:30.

00:35:03.946 --> 00:35:09.756 A:middle
Not this. As with Glances, if
people want to know more detail,

00:35:10.146 --> 00:35:12.856 A:middle
your notification
can offer a deep link

00:35:13.036 --> 00:35:15.466 A:middle
into an appropriate
screen in your app.

00:35:16.696 --> 00:35:18.956 A:middle
Now, most notifications
contain only text.

00:35:19.356 --> 00:35:20.046 A:middle
And that's great.

00:35:20.476 --> 00:35:23.066 A:middle
But in some cases
you can use graphics

00:35:23.106 --> 00:35:24.446 A:middle
to communicate more quickly.

00:35:25.256 --> 00:35:27.076 A:middle
Like this notification
from the fitness

00:35:27.076 --> 00:35:28.946 A:middle
and diet tracker app Life Sum.

00:35:29.416 --> 00:35:32.566 A:middle
They use graphics for many of
the notifications they send.

00:35:33.216 --> 00:35:36.146 A:middle
Obviously this one is a
reminder to drink water.

00:35:37.276 --> 00:35:38.236 A:middle
But the real power

00:35:38.236 --> 00:35:41.256 A:middle
of notifications isn't
just how they inform people

00:35:41.466 --> 00:35:42.856 A:middle
about the things that matter.

00:35:43.256 --> 00:35:46.266 A:middle
They are also a convenient
way for people to take action.

00:35:47.126 --> 00:35:49.646 A:middle
By seeing actions
presented in a notification,

00:35:50.126 --> 00:35:52.336 A:middle
people know that it's
possible to take action

00:35:52.666 --> 00:35:55.196 A:middle
and they know what their
choices for acting are.

00:35:56.536 --> 00:35:59.866 A:middle
Interactive notifications
are really about triage.



00:36:00.326 --> 00:36:01.886 A:middle
You should think
about it in this way.

00:36:02.426 --> 00:36:05.276 A:middle
People receive timely
or urgent information

00:36:05.556 --> 00:36:07.256 A:middle
and they can take
immediate action.

00:36:07.966 --> 00:36:11.526 A:middle
Only display the most
relevant action or actions.

00:36:12.336 --> 00:36:15.936 A:middle
So, for example, the new message
notification gives you just one

00:36:15.936 --> 00:36:17.406 A:middle
option, to reply.

00:36:18.306 --> 00:36:20.416 A:middle
Now, other actions could
have been presented here,

00:36:20.666 --> 00:36:22.826 A:middle
but this is hands-down
the most likely choice

00:36:22.876 --> 00:36:24.316 A:middle
that anyone would want to make.

00:36:24.876 --> 00:36:28.376 A:middle
Okay. Enough about
notifications.

00:36:29.036 --> 00:36:31.816 A:middle
Let's turn to how you can
support lightweight interaction

00:36:32.106 --> 00:36:33.016 A:middle
in your apps.

00:36:33.756 --> 00:36:36.776 A:middle
Apps and games in Apple
Watch should be far simpler

00:36:36.806 --> 00:36:39.676 A:middle
than the typical
iPhone app or game.

00:36:40.946 --> 00:36:45.266 A:middle
You must always remember Apple
Watch is not a miniature iPhone.

00:36:45.626 --> 00:36:49.756 A:middle
I have seen countless developers
trying to take the entirety

00:36:49.756 --> 00:36:54.106 A:middle
of their iPhone app experience
and cram it into a Watch app.

00:36:54.746 --> 00:36:57.116 A:middle
That is a recipe for disaster.

00:36:57.536 --> 00:37:01.426 A:middle
It leads to overly complicated
apps that are difficult



00:36:57.536 --> 00:37:01.426 A:middle
It leads to overly complicated
apps that are difficult

00:37:01.426 --> 00:37:03.906 A:middle
or impossible to
use and navigate.

00:37:04.796 --> 00:37:07.846 A:middle
To be totally clear, making
an Apple Watch app to be

00:37:07.846 --> 00:37:10.046 A:middle
like your iPhone
app is a non-goal.

00:37:11.096 --> 00:37:14.576 A:middle
The goal instead should be
to design an Apple Watch app

00:37:14.576 --> 00:37:16.896 A:middle
that complements
your iPhone app.

00:37:17.466 --> 00:37:21.326 A:middle
This may involve hand picking
just one or two key functions

00:37:21.626 --> 00:37:23.356 A:middle
and bringing it over
to Apple Watch.

00:37:24.406 --> 00:37:27.296 A:middle
Or it could be creating an
entirely different experience

00:37:27.836 --> 00:37:28.726 A:middle
for Apple Watch.

00:37:29.856 --> 00:37:32.056 A:middle
Whatever you do, focus
on the essentials.

00:37:32.486 --> 00:37:35.666 A:middle
Don't present too much
information or functionality.

00:37:36.406 --> 00:37:39.576 A:middle
Only include the things
that people truly want quick

00:37:39.576 --> 00:37:41.096 A:middle
and convenient access to.

00:37:42.076 --> 00:37:43.736 A:middle
Let's look at a couple
of examples.

00:37:44.666 --> 00:37:48.526 A:middle
Green Kitchen on iOS is an
awesome cooking app with lots

00:37:48.526 --> 00:37:51.266 A:middle
of delicious recipes,
ingredient lists

00:37:51.386 --> 00:37:52.796 A:middle
and step-by-step instructions.

00:37:53.826 --> 00:37:57.676 A:middle
Technically they could have
done all of this on Apple Watch,

00:37:58.446 --> 00:38:01.106 A:middle
but they took a different
approach and focused



00:37:58.446 --> 00:38:01.106 A:middle
but they took a different
approach and focused

00:38:01.106 --> 00:38:03.706 A:middle
on something simple
which is timers.

00:38:04.516 --> 00:38:06.866 A:middle
While you are cooking with one
of their recipes, you'll notice

00:38:06.866 --> 00:38:09.826 A:middle
that the times are highlighted
in green, and if you tap one

00:38:09.826 --> 00:38:13.346 A:middle
of those times, it will start
a timer which you can monitor

00:38:13.346 --> 00:38:18.306 A:middle
on your iPhone but also
monitor it on your Apple Watch.

00:38:19.276 --> 00:38:21.806 A:middle
Their Apple Watch app is
a quick and convenient way

00:38:21.806 --> 00:38:24.456 A:middle
to see how much time is
left in the current step.

00:38:25.266 --> 00:38:26.326 A:middle
Of course you can choose

00:38:26.326 --> 00:38:29.616 A:middle
to receive notifications
when the timer is up.

00:38:30.546 --> 00:38:33.276 A:middle
Let's look at the
New York Times app.

00:38:33.346 --> 00:38:38.036 A:middle
Now, on the iPhone they have
tons and tons of content.

00:38:38.786 --> 00:38:40.656 A:middle
You can access all
of their editorials

00:38:40.656 --> 00:38:41.956 A:middle
and articles and more.

00:38:42.596 --> 00:38:46.426 A:middle
Again, doing this on Apple
Watch is technically possible,

00:38:46.426 --> 00:38:49.316 A:middle
but it would be a
terrible, terrible idea.

00:38:49.316 --> 00:38:50.006 A:middle
Don't do that.

00:38:50.706 --> 00:38:52.276 A:middle
Just browsing through the list

00:38:52.276 --> 00:38:54.936 A:middle
of sections alone would
take way too long.

00:38:55.326 --> 00:38:57.106 A:middle
No one in their right mind wants

00:38:57.106 --> 00:38:59.256 A:middle
to read a thousand word
article on their wrist.



00:39:00.326 --> 00:39:02.206 A:middle
Instead the New York Times app

00:39:02.206 --> 00:39:06.226 A:middle
for Apple Watch only shows
a curated set of top stories

00:39:06.916 --> 00:39:10.396 A:middle
that their editorial team
has hand crafted just

00:39:10.396 --> 00:39:11.406 A:middle
for the Apple Watch.

00:39:12.276 --> 00:39:14.856 A:middle
They only show what they
believe are the most important

00:39:14.856 --> 00:39:16.396 A:middle
and timely news stories.

00:39:17.246 --> 00:39:20.296 A:middle
Each story is really
just a quick synopsis.

00:39:20.856 --> 00:39:23.246 A:middle
It is not, they are not
displaying full articles.

00:39:24.206 --> 00:39:27.116 A:middle
Reading the full story
would take way more

00:39:27.346 --> 00:39:29.466 A:middle
than two to five seconds.

00:39:30.996 --> 00:39:33.976 A:middle
If people want to continue
reading, there's a save

00:39:33.976 --> 00:39:37.056 A:middle
for later action in the menu
so they can bookmark a story

00:39:37.056 --> 00:39:38.856 A:middle
and read it later on
the iPhone or iPad.

00:39:39.856 --> 00:39:42.536 A:middle
Or they can take
out their iPhone

00:39:42.956 --> 00:39:44.216 A:middle
and continue reading more.

00:39:44.846 --> 00:39:46.546 A:middle
It's natural behavior.

00:39:47.196 --> 00:39:51.236 A:middle
That is why it's so important
to implement hand-off.

00:39:52.326 --> 00:39:54.896 A:middle
When the New York Times reader
transitions from the Watch

00:39:54.896 --> 00:39:57.256 A:middle
to their iPhone, they may notice

00:39:57.256 --> 00:40:00.106 A:middle
on their lock screen the
New York Times app icon.



00:39:57.256 --> 00:40:00.106 A:middle
on their lock screen the
New York Times app icon.

00:40:00.936 --> 00:40:03.616 A:middle
Swiping that up will take
them directly to the story

00:40:03.616 --> 00:40:05.716 A:middle
that they are reading
on the AppleWatch.

00:40:06.956 --> 00:40:10.436 A:middle
Hand off makes it easy for
the New York Times reader

00:40:10.686 --> 00:40:13.676 A:middle
to move seamlessly from
their Watch to their iPhone

00:40:13.676 --> 00:40:14.696 A:middle
when they want to know more.

00:40:15.556 --> 00:40:18.136 A:middle
This benefits the New York
Times reader, of course,

00:40:18.676 --> 00:40:20.716 A:middle
but also benefits
the New York Times

00:40:20.716 --> 00:40:23.886 A:middle
because it keeps people
engaged with their experience,

00:40:23.886 --> 00:40:26.366 A:middle
their apps for a
longer period of time.

00:40:27.366 --> 00:40:29.706 A:middle
Hand-off is relatively new.

00:40:30.246 --> 00:40:33.406 A:middle
You may feel the need to
educate your users about it.

00:40:33.406 --> 00:40:36.016 A:middle
As a matter of fact, the
New York Times does this.

00:40:36.636 --> 00:40:39.746 A:middle
In the first launch onboarding
experience they show a tip

00:40:39.746 --> 00:40:41.146 A:middle
about how it works.

00:40:41.826 --> 00:40:45.206 A:middle
Otherwise, they just rely upon
people naturally discovering

00:40:45.206 --> 00:40:47.946 A:middle
this function on their own.

00:40:47.946 --> 00:40:50.066 A:middle
Now, other apps take
a different approach.

00:40:50.546 --> 00:40:50.826 A:middle
This is CNN.

00:40:50.826 --> 00:40:53.346 A:middle
Soon they will be
taking advantage

00:40:53.346 --> 00:40:55.696 A:middle
of the video play back
capabilities of the Apple Watch

00:40:56.136 --> 00:40:59.926 A:middle
to provide short video
clips from their content.



00:41:00.626 --> 00:41:03.506 A:middle
Now, they are going to
also provide a little bit

00:41:03.506 --> 00:41:06.216 A:middle
of instruction that
says people can continue

00:41:06.216 --> 00:41:08.526 A:middle
to watch the full
video on their iPhone.

00:41:09.246 --> 00:41:11.336 A:middle
That is really good
information to have

00:41:11.406 --> 00:41:13.136 A:middle
because without it
you wouldn't know

00:41:13.436 --> 00:41:15.276 A:middle
that there's a longer
version of the video.

00:41:15.826 --> 00:41:17.236 A:middle
This is useful information.

00:41:18.426 --> 00:41:21.606 A:middle
CNN also shows this little
monochromatic version

00:41:21.606 --> 00:41:24.546 A:middle
of their iOS icon which
is a pretty clever trick

00:41:24.546 --> 00:41:26.466 A:middle
for priming people to spot it

00:41:26.466 --> 00:41:29.946 A:middle
when they go over
to their iPhone.

00:41:30.046 --> 00:41:33.756 A:middle
Both CNN and the New York
Times provide good examples

00:41:34.106 --> 00:41:36.696 A:middle
of how you can communicate that
your app supports hand off.

00:41:37.486 --> 00:41:41.856 A:middle
However, over time this may
become less necessary as more

00:41:41.856 --> 00:41:43.956 A:middle
and more people will
expect that all

00:41:43.956 --> 00:41:46.016 A:middle
of your apps will
support hand-off.

00:41:46.696 --> 00:41:49.596 A:middle
It's up to you to decide
what's right for your app.

00:41:49.786 --> 00:41:52.386 A:middle
If you are concerned that people
won't realize there's more

00:41:52.386 --> 00:41:55.176 A:middle
information or functionality
which is available

00:41:55.176 --> 00:41:58.226 A:middle
on your iPhone app, by
all means, let them know.

00:41:58.356 --> 00:42:00.406 A:middle
That's helpful to your users.



00:41:58.356 --> 00:42:00.406 A:middle
That's helpful to your users.

00:42:00.886 --> 00:42:04.186 A:middle
Otherwise, just let people
discover it on their own.

00:42:05.176 --> 00:42:06.596 A:middle
Now, that said, there's
one thing

00:42:06.596 --> 00:42:09.616 A:middle
which is almost never required
when it comes to hand-off.

00:42:10.196 --> 00:42:12.076 A:middle
That is showing a
butt-in for hand-off.

00:42:12.806 --> 00:42:16.696 A:middle
Only in rare circumstances is
it ever necessary for people

00:42:16.696 --> 00:42:18.046 A:middle
to tap a button in order

00:42:18.046 --> 00:42:20.036 A:middle
to continue an activity
on their iPhone.

00:42:20.476 --> 00:42:22.656 A:middle
Hand-off should happen
automatically.

00:42:23.976 --> 00:42:26.456 A:middle
Now, there's one more aspect
of lightweight interaction

00:42:26.726 --> 00:42:28.126 A:middle
that I would like
to discuss with you.

00:42:28.776 --> 00:42:32.746 A:middle
It relates to health
apps and relates to --

00:42:32.976 --> 00:42:35.366 A:middle
when you are using
HealthKit to track a work out.

00:42:36.876 --> 00:42:39.816 A:middle
More specifically it's
about creating sessions

00:42:39.816 --> 00:42:41.226 A:middle
to keep your app
in the foreground

00:42:41.656 --> 00:42:44.326 A:middle
when you are tracking an
activity like going for a run.

00:42:45.306 --> 00:42:47.886 A:middle
Ordinarily when Apple
Watch has been sleeping

00:42:47.956 --> 00:42:52.326 A:middle
for ar short period of time, it
assumes that the user is done

00:42:52.326 --> 00:42:54.466 A:middle
with doing whatever
they were doing before,

00:42:54.956 --> 00:42:57.436 A:middle
no longer interested in
the app, and it will resume

00:42:57.506 --> 00:43:00.236 A:middle
to the clock face, not
the previously used app.



00:42:57.506 --> 00:43:00.236 A:middle
to the clock face, not
the previously used app.

00:43:01.276 --> 00:43:03.256 A:middle
But this changes when
an app is being used

00:43:03.256 --> 00:43:05.656 A:middle
to track an activity
like going for a run.

00:43:06.846 --> 00:43:09.396 A:middle
While that person is
running, they want to stay

00:43:09.396 --> 00:43:10.766 A:middle
in the activity tracker app,

00:43:11.406 --> 00:43:13.426 A:middle
raising the wrist
should allow them

00:43:13.426 --> 00:43:16.576 A:middle
to quickly check their
progress, which is why

00:43:16.576 --> 00:43:20.656 A:middle
in WatchOS 2 activity
tracker apps will remain

00:43:20.656 --> 00:43:23.016 A:middle
in the foreground while the
HealthKit workout session

00:43:23.016 --> 00:43:23.626 A:middle
is ongoing.

00:43:24.476 --> 00:43:28.496 A:middle
Implemented correctly, sessions
enable lightweight interaction

00:43:28.496 --> 00:43:30.266 A:middle
because simply by
raising your wrist,

00:43:30.736 --> 00:43:33.996 A:middle
you return to the app
you're most interested in.

00:43:33.996 --> 00:43:36.256 A:middle
People don't need to
continually navigate back

00:43:36.256 --> 00:43:37.586 A:middle
to the app from the home screen.

00:43:38.446 --> 00:43:40.856 A:middle
If you intend to
adopt this feature,

00:43:40.856 --> 00:43:43.896 A:middle
there are a few key
things you should consider

00:43:43.896 --> 00:43:44.666 A:middle
and keep in mind.

00:43:45.366 --> 00:43:49.396 A:middle
First and foremost, the person
using your app must always be

00:43:49.396 --> 00:43:50.056 A:middle
in control.

00:43:51.516 --> 00:43:54.916 A:middle
They must deliberately and
knowingly start a workout.

00:43:55.616 --> 00:43:58.666 A:middle
They must always understand
how to end a workout.

00:43:58.756 --> 00:44:02.086 A:middle
And when they look at the
app, it is a really good idea



00:43:58.756 --> 00:44:02.086 A:middle
And when they look at the
app, it is a really good idea

00:44:02.086 --> 00:44:04.276 A:middle
that they understand that
a session is ongoing.

00:44:04.936 --> 00:44:07.536 A:middle
Your app's UI should
be obviously different.

00:44:07.996 --> 00:44:09.296 A:middle
It should be clear to
people that they are

00:44:09.296 --> 00:44:10.916 A:middle
in a special modal state.

00:44:11.656 --> 00:44:14.886 A:middle
The Fitness app provides a good
example for you to reference.

00:44:15.716 --> 00:44:17.646 A:middle
To start a workout
in the Fitness app,

00:44:17.646 --> 00:44:19.066 A:middle
the user taps the start button.

00:44:19.466 --> 00:44:21.556 A:middle
The button literally says start.

00:44:21.776 --> 00:44:22.336 A:middle
It's clear.

00:44:22.816 --> 00:44:25.556 A:middle
After tapping the start button,
there's a three-second count

00:44:25.556 --> 00:44:27.626 A:middle
down that a session
is about to begin.

00:44:28.586 --> 00:44:31.106 A:middle
Ending a work out is
equally straight forward.

00:44:31.386 --> 00:44:32.856 A:middle
You just swipe to the first page

00:44:32.856 --> 00:44:34.656 A:middle
and tap the clearly
marked end button.

00:44:35.166 --> 00:44:38.576 A:middle
This is a consequence.

00:44:38.666 --> 00:44:40.646 A:middle
This is why I don't
set high expectations

00:44:40.646 --> 00:44:41.906 A:middle
for myself when I go for a run.

00:44:42.456 --> 00:44:47.686 A:middle
As a convenience, there's a
second end button in the menu,

00:44:48.186 --> 00:44:50.566 A:middle
but it's a good idea to not
rely upon people knowing

00:44:50.566 --> 00:44:54.026 A:middle
that your app has a menu in
order for them to end a session.

00:44:55.406 --> 00:44:56.956 A:middle
While the workout is ongoing,

00:44:57.066 --> 00:44:59.756 A:middle
the Fitness app UI is
clearly in a different state.

00:44:59.756 --> 00:45:02.546 A:middle
It is obvious, the
UI makes it obvious



00:44:59.756 --> 00:45:02.546 A:middle
It is obvious, the
UI makes it obvious

00:45:02.546 --> 00:45:03.846 A:middle
that it is recording a work out.

00:45:04.866 --> 00:45:07.456 A:middle
Sessions are about convenience.

00:45:07.506 --> 00:45:09.116 A:middle
They are not about
keeping people

00:45:09.116 --> 00:45:10.546 A:middle
in your app against their will.

00:45:11.226 --> 00:45:14.856 A:middle
If the session started
without the user's knowledge

00:45:14.856 --> 00:45:16.856 A:middle
or it's difficult for them
to figure out how to end it

00:45:17.166 --> 00:45:18.936 A:middle
or it is not clear
that one is ongoing,

00:45:18.986 --> 00:45:21.566 A:middle
they will likely feel
stuck in your app

00:45:21.566 --> 00:45:23.526 A:middle
and that is not a
great experience.

00:45:24.826 --> 00:45:28.016 A:middle
So let's take stock.

00:45:28.186 --> 00:45:30.536 A:middle
I think that was a lot of stuff.

00:45:30.536 --> 00:45:31.196 A:middle
I want to review.

00:45:31.966 --> 00:45:35.036 A:middle
Personal communication is
about applying what we know

00:45:35.036 --> 00:45:38.366 A:middle
about thoughtful and effective
interpersonal communication

00:45:38.706 --> 00:45:40.476 A:middle
to the design of your apps.

00:45:40.896 --> 00:45:43.986 A:middle
It is about being respectful
of people's time and attention

00:45:44.356 --> 00:45:46.906 A:middle
by being concise,
relevant and responsive

00:45:46.976 --> 00:45:49.916 A:middle
to the person's individual
preferences.

00:45:50.696 --> 00:45:52.906 A:middle
Holistic Design is about
blurring the boundaries

00:45:52.906 --> 00:45:54.746 A:middle
between software and hardware

00:45:55.096 --> 00:45:57.946 A:middle
by making your app's UI
practically indistinguishable

00:45:58.306 --> 00:45:59.276 A:middle
from the Watch bezel.



00:46:00.086 --> 00:46:03.356 A:middle
Utilizing the Force Touch
display to enable quick access

00:46:03.786 --> 00:46:06.156 A:middle
for contextual actions
or preferences.

00:46:07.076 --> 00:46:09.836 A:middle
Knowing that scrolling is
easy so there's no need

00:46:09.896 --> 00:46:13.536 A:middle
for cramped UIs, and using
the new Picker to enable quick

00:46:13.536 --> 00:46:16.316 A:middle
and accurate selections
in context.

00:46:16.896 --> 00:46:19.786 A:middle
And using haptic feedback
to create sophisticated

00:46:19.786 --> 00:46:24.206 A:middle
and more deeply life like
experiences in your app.

00:46:24.206 --> 00:46:27.436 A:middle
And lightweight interaction
is about offering people quick

00:46:27.436 --> 00:46:30.936 A:middle
and convenient access to
information and actions.

00:46:32.026 --> 00:46:35.116 A:middle
Now, these three themes
should be the foundation upon

00:46:35.116 --> 00:46:38.246 A:middle
which you design
your Apple Watch app.

00:46:41.056 --> 00:46:42.356 A:middle
But there's something
missing here.

00:46:42.356 --> 00:46:45.426 A:middle
There is something that
these three themes don't

00:46:45.586 --> 00:46:46.536 A:middle
adequately capture.

00:46:47.536 --> 00:46:49.806 A:middle
That is the role of
beauty and delight.

00:46:51.166 --> 00:46:55.306 A:middle
Apps that are beautiful and
delight us make our experience

00:46:55.306 --> 00:46:57.256 A:middle
with technology more
interesting,

00:46:57.776 --> 00:47:00.066 A:middle
more welcoming and more fun.



00:46:57.776 --> 00:47:00.066 A:middle
more welcoming and more fun.

00:47:01.176 --> 00:47:03.586 A:middle
Even though the Apple
Watch display is small,

00:47:03.666 --> 00:47:06.596 A:middle
there is still plenty of
space to make it beautiful.

00:47:07.456 --> 00:47:09.596 A:middle
Even though interaction
times are meant to be brief,

00:47:09.596 --> 00:47:11.796 A:middle
there's still plenty
of time to delight.

00:47:12.576 --> 00:47:16.076 A:middle
I would like to share with
you three of my favorite apps

00:47:16.516 --> 00:47:19.096 A:middle
that are really exemplars
of this concept.

00:47:20.516 --> 00:47:23.136 A:middle
Resound makes Bluetooth
